00:05:02,600 --> 00:05:05,940
Ethereum as infrastructure for deep self sovereignty

130
00:05:05,940 --> 00:05:07,560
by Shreem Shinder,

131
00:05:07,560 --> 00:05:11,880
team lead of academic secretariat at Ethereum Foundation.

132
00:05:11,880 --> 00:05:13,220
Please welcome Shreem.

133
00:05:28,010 --> 00:05:30,810
Thank you so much everyone for coming down today

134
00:05:30,810 --> 00:05:33,950
and for having me to give this talk.

135
00:05:33,950 --> 00:05:37,490
So today I'm going to talk about two things.

136
00:05:37,490 --> 00:05:40,450
The first thing is that Ethereum is probably

137
00:05:40,450 --> 00:05:43,210
history's first very serious attempt

138
00:05:43,210 --> 00:05:45,050
at actually building infrastructures

139
00:05:45,050 --> 00:05:48,610
that can allow for deep and complete self sovereignty.

140
00:05:48,610 --> 00:05:52,130
And I'm also gonna talk about how researchers

141
00:05:52,130 --> 00:05:53,810
and everyone in this room in fact

142
00:05:53,810 --> 00:05:56,050
has a very critical role to play

143
00:05:56,050 --> 00:06:01,070
in order to ensure that we succeed in this attempt.

144
00:06:01,070 --> 00:06:04,950
So let me first talk about the context

145
00:06:04,950 --> 00:06:08,850
or rather the problem that motivated a lot of things

146
00:06:08,850 --> 00:06:10,630
that we see today in the Ethereum space.

147
00:06:10,630 --> 00:06:14,050
A problem that many scholars had spent years

148
00:06:14,050 --> 00:06:17,390
and almost their entire careers trying to solve.

149
00:06:17,390 --> 00:06:21,090
The problem of how can humans effectively coordinate

150
00:06:21,090 --> 00:06:23,510
without explicitly trusting the system

151
00:06:23,510 --> 00:06:25,890
that they used for coordination.

152
00:06:25,890 --> 00:06:28,690
So there have been a lot of very serious scholars

153
00:06:28,690 --> 00:06:31,850
like Ostrom and Hobbes who've spent their entire careers

154
00:06:31,850 --> 00:06:32,810
trying to solve this problem.

155
00:06:32,810 --> 00:06:35,250
But the unfortunate reality is that

156
00:06:35,250 --> 00:06:36,450
it's not until very recently

157
00:06:36,450 --> 00:06:39,250
that a viable solution was found.

158
00:06:39,250 --> 00:06:40,210
And as a result of that,

159
00:06:40,210 --> 00:06:43,430
a lot of the systems that we see today in the world

160
00:06:43,430 --> 00:06:45,410
actually build around this problem

161
00:06:45,410 --> 00:06:48,610
rather than trying to solve this problem heads on.

162
00:06:49,890 --> 00:06:52,370
Which is why we see that a lot of the systems

163
00:06:52,370 --> 00:06:53,810
that we deal with in today's world

164
00:06:53,810 --> 00:06:57,650
actually has what is called a back door.

165
00:06:57,650 --> 00:07:02,330
So for example, if you look at systems like banking systems,

166
00:07:02,330 --> 00:07:06,070
it's very easy for the centralized authorities

167
00:07:06,070 --> 00:07:07,510
to freeze your account.

168
00:07:07,510 --> 00:07:10,010
If you look at platforms, whether it's social media platforms

169
00:07:10,010 --> 00:07:12,270
or whether it's gaming platforms,

170
00:07:12,270 --> 00:07:15,930
it's very easy in the name of violation

171
00:07:15,930 --> 00:07:19,090
of an arbitrary set of rules of conduct.

172
00:07:19,090 --> 00:07:21,770
It's very easy for people to get deplatformed

173
00:07:21,770 --> 00:07:26,770
without possibly serious reasons for it.

174
00:07:26,770 --> 00:07:28,570
And now with the advent of AI,

175
00:07:28,570 --> 00:07:30,490
we have a whole new set of back doors,

176
00:07:30,490 --> 00:07:33,290
which is the models that we use

177
00:07:33,290 --> 00:07:35,210
or we heavily depend on today.

178
00:07:35,210 --> 00:07:37,490
They can very arbitrarily be withdrawn.

179
00:07:37,490 --> 00:07:39,010
Their API can be shut down

180
00:07:39,010 --> 00:07:40,290
and their rates could be locked down,

181
00:07:40,290 --> 00:07:42,290
meaning that no new training happens.

182
00:07:42,290 --> 00:07:44,170
And all of this just goes to say that

183
00:07:44,170 --> 00:07:47,010
back doors structurally exist in most systems around us.

184
00:07:47,890 --> 00:07:49,970
Now, I don't want to talk about what would happen

185
00:07:49,970 --> 00:07:50,870
if they are exercised,

186
00:07:50,870 --> 00:07:53,950
because that is often considered an edge case

187
00:07:53,950 --> 00:07:57,210
and those really vary from scenario to scenario.

188
00:07:57,210 --> 00:07:59,670
But I'd like to make the point that the very fact

189
00:07:59,670 --> 00:08:03,590
that they exist itself shapes behavior of its users.

190
00:08:03,590 --> 00:08:04,790
And this is a very important point

191
00:08:04,790 --> 00:08:06,510
because it's not about whether they get exercised,

192
00:08:06,510 --> 00:08:09,590
but it's about whether they structurally actually exist.

193
00:08:09,590 --> 00:08:12,790
So people can preemptively self-censor

194
00:08:12,790 --> 00:08:14,950
under the fear of getting deplatformed.

195
00:08:14,950 --> 00:08:17,270
People can preemptively not build things

196
00:08:17,270 --> 00:08:18,630
that actually need to be built.

197
00:08:18,630 --> 00:08:20,470
And in very extreme cases,

198
00:08:20,470 --> 00:08:23,970
they can even try to circumvent some of these systems,

199
00:08:23,970 --> 00:08:27,390
which ends up causing more harm than it does good.

200
00:08:27,390 --> 00:08:30,270
So that's the fundamental reality

201
00:08:30,270 --> 00:08:36,040
that structural dependencies actually shape user behavior,

202
00:08:36,040 --> 00:08:38,760
which brings us to think about the question of,

203
00:08:38,760 --> 00:08:41,760
okay, is it possible for this back door

204
00:08:41,760 --> 00:08:43,280
to not exist by construction?

205
00:08:43,280 --> 00:08:44,120
Is it possible?

206
00:08:44,120 --> 00:08:45,840
And what would happen in a scenario

207
00:08:45,840 --> 00:08:48,240
where there is no back door?

208
00:08:48,280 --> 00:08:51,500
And I think cryptography was the first serious tool.

209
00:08:52,320 --> 00:08:54,240
And using it for the first time,

210
00:08:54,240 --> 00:08:57,000
you could actually build technical primitives

211
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:58,680
to help humans coordinate,

212
00:08:58,680 --> 00:09:01,920
where arbitrary revocability is not just an edge case,

213
00:09:01,920 --> 00:09:04,200
or it's not just an unlikely scenario,

214
00:09:04,200 --> 00:09:06,800
but it's architecturally impossible.

215
00:09:06,800 --> 00:09:07,860
And the question was, okay,

216
00:09:07,860 --> 00:09:10,760
now that we have these beautiful tools,

217
00:09:10,760 --> 00:09:13,400
is it possible to make these programmable?

218
00:09:13,400 --> 00:09:15,960
Is it possible to make these composable?

219
00:09:15,960 --> 00:09:17,880
And is it possible to make it available

220
00:09:17,880 --> 00:09:21,650
at a large scale for everyone?

221
00:09:21,650 --> 00:09:24,890
And that's kind of where Ethereum comes into play.

222
00:09:24,890 --> 00:09:27,690
And then that's, in many sense,

223
00:09:27,690 --> 00:09:30,970
a lot of the motivations behind why Ethereum exists

224
00:09:30,970 --> 00:09:32,390
and why a lot of the applications

225
00:09:32,390 --> 00:09:35,290
that are built on top of Ethereum exist.

226
00:09:35,290 --> 00:09:37,890
So Ethereum's claim is very precise, right?

227
00:09:37,890 --> 00:09:39,650
It's programmable in the sense that

228
00:09:39,650 --> 00:09:42,450
any rule can be specified and can be enforced

229
00:09:42,450 --> 00:09:44,250
without a trusted third party.

230
00:09:44,250 --> 00:09:48,210
It's composable in the sense that it guarantees stack.

231
00:09:48,290 --> 00:09:50,330
And I'm gonna talk about this a little more

232
00:09:50,330 --> 00:09:51,530
in the next few slides,

233
00:09:51,530 --> 00:09:53,430
but also it's available at scale,

234
00:09:53,430 --> 00:09:55,330
which means that anyone, anywhere,

235
00:09:55,330 --> 00:09:57,590
without permission from any platform,

236
00:09:57,590 --> 00:10:00,410
can actually take part in the system.

237
00:10:01,610 --> 00:10:05,410
And each of these properties has, in the past,

238
00:10:05,410 --> 00:10:07,730
been attempted in some shape or form,

239
00:10:07,730 --> 00:10:09,570
but it's almost for the first time

240
00:10:09,570 --> 00:10:13,410
that all these three guarantees can be achieved

241
00:10:13,410 --> 00:10:14,810
at this very same time.

242
00:10:14,810 --> 00:10:17,090
And that's kind of Ethereum's claim.

243
00:10:18,810 --> 00:10:20,890
But the truth is, it actually doesn't end

244
00:10:20,890 --> 00:10:22,330
at the protocol layer.

245
00:10:22,330 --> 00:10:26,170
So in Aya's talk, she had briefly touched upon

246
00:10:26,170 --> 00:10:28,110
how there are very important decisions

247
00:10:28,110 --> 00:10:31,810
and important constraints and trade-offs to be considered

248
00:10:31,810 --> 00:10:33,650
while designing the protocol layer.

249
00:10:33,650 --> 00:10:37,530
But the harsh reality is that, given that every,

250
00:10:37,530 --> 00:10:39,130
like given that the system is composable

251
00:10:39,130 --> 00:10:41,870
and every piece of stack just goes one on top of the other,

252
00:10:41,870 --> 00:10:43,490
even if the protocol is built

253
00:10:43,490 --> 00:10:47,510
keeping all these properties in mind,

254
00:10:47,510 --> 00:10:49,150
anywhere in the stack,

255
00:10:49,150 --> 00:10:53,510
if that notion of self-sovereignty is broken,

256
00:10:53,510 --> 00:10:55,710
then it never reaches the user.

257
00:10:55,710 --> 00:10:57,990
So even at the consensus layer, execution layer,

258
00:10:57,990 --> 00:10:59,870
or, very importantly, the application layer,

259
00:10:59,870 --> 00:11:01,190
if things break down,

260
00:11:01,190 --> 00:11:03,970
these guarantees that we want to give to the final user

261
00:11:03,970 --> 00:11:06,070
can never actually reach the final user.

262
00:11:07,390 --> 00:11:09,470
So just to make it a little more concrete,

263
00:11:09,470 --> 00:11:12,430
here are some very concrete examples or scenarios

264
00:11:13,270 --> 00:11:15,710
where these aspirations could actually break down.

265
00:11:15,710 --> 00:11:17,350
So if you look at RPC concentration,

266
00:11:18,230 --> 00:11:20,990
in a scenario where there are only two to three providers

267
00:11:20,990 --> 00:11:24,390
which stand between most users and the protocol,

268
00:11:24,390 --> 00:11:27,770
coordinated censorship by these handful of providers

269
00:11:27,770 --> 00:11:29,410
